Rome was meanwhile disturbed by the riots of Clodius, who looked forward to obtaining the aedileship and thus es- caping the punishment due to his lawless acts. In spite of the attempts of Milo, as tribune, to hinder the comitia sor the election of aediles and of the proposal of L. Racilius20 for a legal inquiry into his conduct, Clodius was chosen curule aedile next year on the 22nd of January. The first thing he did was to commence a prosecution against Milo which, however, he was forced to drop. He then instigated M. Tullius Albino- vanus to charge P. Sestius, the late tribune, with a breach of the peace. One of Cicero's most important orations was in desence of his friend and supporter‚ who was acquitted by the votes of all the jurymen21 on the 13th of March.
